Project description¶

AllLife Bank wants to focus on its credit card customer base in the next financial year. They have been advised by their marketing research team, that the penetration in the market can be improved. Based on this input, the Marketing team proposes to run personalized campaigns to target new customers as well as upsell to existing customers. Another insight from the market research was that the customers perceive the support services of the back poorly. Based on this, the Operations team wants to upgrade the service delivery model, to ensure that customer queries are resolved faster.

Objective¶

To identify different segments in the existing customer, based on their spending patterns as well as past interaction with the bank, using clustering algorithms, and provide recommendations to the bank on how to better market to and service these customers.

Data Description¶

The data provided is of various customers of a bank and their financial attributes like credit limit, the total number of credit cards the customer has, and different channels through which customers have contacted the bank for any queries (including visiting the bank, online and through a call center).

Data Dictionary¶

  • Sl_No: Primary key of the records
  • Customer Key: Customer identification number
  • Average Credit Limit: Average credit limit of each customer for all credit cards
  • Total credit cards: Total number of credit cards possessed by the customer
  • Total visits bank: Total number of visits that customer made (yearly) personally to the bank
  • Total visits online: Total number of visits or online logins made by the customer (yearly)
  • Total calls made: Total number of calls made by the customer to the bank or its customer service department (yearly)

# function to plot a boxplot and a histogram along the same scale.


def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(12, 7), kde=False, bins=None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (12,7))
    kde: whether to the show density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )  # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet"
    )  # boxplot will be created and a star will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins, palette="winter"
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2
    )  # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--"
    )  # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-"
    )  # Add median to the histogram

Through kdeplots, we can observe a few variable pairs to start to form clear clusters. Most notably:

  • Unsurprisingly, clients that have lower credit limits have a lower number of credit cards while people with credit limits above 100,000 tend to have the highest number of credit cards
  • Furthermore, customers with lower credit limits perform a lower number of online visits
  • This also translates to customers that perform online banking the most, consistently have a high number of credit cards
  • Clients with the highest online visits (+5) also perform the least amount of calls to the bank

There also seem to be strong correlative relationships between multiple variables can be further explored through correlation heatmap.

In [ ]:
sns.heatmap(data_df.corr(),annot=True)
Out[ ]:
<AxesSubplot: >

Various important patterns elucidate further here:

  • Customers' visits to the bank are inversely proportional to the total visits online. This would suggest that the online/remote banking services are adequate for customers to actually solve their issues. This could also be an indicator of a distinction between tech savvy customer versus not.
  • There is also a strong negative correlation between the total number of credit cards and the total number of calls made to the bank. On the other hand, there is a lightly positive correlation between the number of credit cards and bank visits and online visits.
  • There is a positive correlation between the average credit limit and visits online, while this postiive correlation is decreased when seen in the context of number of credit cards, despite credit limit and credit card number being highly correlated. This 'discrepancy' would possibly provide insights on the credit size per card between customers performing online banking

To further visualize these relationships it would be advantageous to present the counts (as density) for each othe pairplots.

def density(df,x,y):
    bins = 10
    H, xedges, yedges = np.histogram2d(df[x],df[y])
    H = H.T    
    return H, xedges, yedges

K-means clustering¶

In [ ]:
#Finding optimal no. of clusters

clusters=range(2,10)
meanDistortions=[]
silh_scores = []

for k in clusters:
    model=KMeans(n_clusters=k)
    model.fit(norm_df)
    
    # prediction=model.predict(techSuppScaled)
    c_dist = cdist(norm_df, model.cluster_centers_, 'euclidean')
    minc_dist = np.min(c_dist, axis=1)
    meanDistortions.append(sum(minc_dist) / norm_df.shape[0])

    pred = model.fit_predict(norm_df)
    silh_scores.append(silhouette_score(norm_df, pred))

fig = plt.figure(figsize=(15,5))
fig.add_subplot(121)
plt.plot(clusters, meanDistortions, 'bx-')
plt.xlabel('k')
plt.ylabel('Average distortion')
plt.title('Selecting k with the Elbow Method')

fig.add_subplot(122)
plt.plot(clusters,silh_scores, 'kx-')
plt.xlabel('k')
plt.ylabel('Silhouette Score')
plt.title('Selecting k with Silhouette Scores')

#To account for possible high variability, we can perform Silhouette Plots for the three highest silhouette scores

from yellowbrick.cluster import SilhouetteVisualizer

fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 3, figsize=(15,8))
for ind,i in enumerate([2,3,4]):
    '''
    Create KMeans instance for different number of clusters
    '''
    km = KMeans(n_clusters=i)
    q, mod = divmod(i, 2)
    '''
    Create SilhouetteVisualizer instance with KMeans instance
    Fit the visualizer
    '''
    visualizer = SilhouetteVisualizer(km, colors='yellowbrick',ax=ax[ind])
    visualizer.fit(norm_df)

    plt.suptitle('Silhouette plots for k = 2,3,4')

We see that we maximize cluster separation at n=3, and all clusters are above the mean S.score line. Therefore </b>k=3</b> is the cluster selection for K-Means approach

Customer Profiling¶

  • Group 1
    • This group interacts with the bank most by in person visits, and they have credit limits below the 30th precentile (with a mean of ~33k) with an average of 5 credit cards
  • Group 2
    • This group interacts with the bank most by calling. They have the lowest credit limit out of the groups below the 20th percentile (with a mean of ~12.5k) and only 2 credit cards on average
  • Group 3
    • This group interacts with the bank most by online banking. They have the highest credit limit (with around ~150k), and the highest number of credit cards.

Comparing distance metrics across the general linkage methods¶

In [ ]:
# list of distance metrics
distance_metrics = ["euclidean", "chebyshev", "mahalanobis", "cityblock"]

# list of linkage methods
linkage_methods = ["single", "complete", "average", "weighted"]

high_cophenet_corr = 0
high_dm_lm = [0, 0]

for dm in distance_metrics:
    for lm in linkage_methods:
        Z = linkage(norm_df, metric=dm, method=lm)
        c, coph_dists = cophenet(Z, pdist(norm_df))
        print(
            "Cophenetic correlation for {} distance and {} linkage is {}.".format(
                dm.capitalize(), lm, c
            )
        )
        if high_cophenet_corr < c:
            high_cophenet_corr = c
            high_dm_lm[0] = dm
            high_dm_lm[1] = lm
    print()

In [ ]:
# list of linkage methods
linkage_methods = ["single", "complete", "average", "centroid", "ward", "weighted"]

# lists to save results of cophenetic correlation calculation
compare_cols = ["Linkage", "Cophenetic Coefficient"]
compare = []

# to create a subplot image
fig, axs = plt.subplots(len(linkage_methods), 1, figsize=(15, 30))

# We will enumerate through the list of linkage methods above
# For each linkage method, we will plot the dendrogram and calculate the cophenetic correlation
for i, method in enumerate(linkage_methods):
    Z = linkage(norm_df, metric="euclidean", method=method)

    dendrogram(Z, ax=axs[i])
    axs[i].set_title(f"Dendrogram from Euclidian distance ({method.capitalize()} Linkage)")

    coph_corr, coph_dist = cophenet(Z, pdist(norm_df))
    
    axs[i].annotate(
        f"Cophenetic\nCorrelation\n{coph_corr:0.4f}",
        (0.80, 0.80),
        xycoords="axes fraction",
    )

    compare.append([method, coph_corr])

Given that Cityblock also gave really high Cophenetic values, we should also observe the resulting dendrograms.

Customer Profiling¶

We can see that these clusters match the observations made with K-Means clustering approach.

K-Means vs Hierarchical Clustering¶

By grouping variables by the Hierarchical Clusters (while including GROUP variable from the K-Means Clustering) we observe that there was no difference in the assignment of clustering grouping between the two methods, since the mean values of variable GROUP are integers. I.e.:

  • K-means group 1 pertains to HCluster group 1
  • K-means group 2 pertains to HCluster group 3
  • K-means group 3 pertains to HCluster group 2

Actionable insights and recommendations:¶

  • Most of their clientele has credit limit is skewed below the 10% percentile of the consumer base.
    • Therefore, I would recommend special attention being given to clients with low credit limits (especially in the median range of number of credit cards held). These clients likely pertain to consumers starting to increase their credit score. Instituting features online to handle many cards and how to combine them to facilitate credit building could be very advantageous.
  • Most customers are not really taking advantage of the online banking
    • The ones that are, are people with high credit limits (likely high credit scores in response) and the highest number of credit cards. Online ads should be carefully selected as this cluster would be business and financially savvy. However, this would be the main point of contact for this cluster.
  • Customers that frequent going to the bank would rather call than visit online.
    • With the exception of people who call frequently, or frequently go to the bank
    • This cluster should be a large focus of the bank as their credit limits are higher, they purchase >2-fold more credit products from the bank and they are the largest percentage of the customer base
    • Given that average CC holders rather go to the bank than call, despite being such a large percentage of the customer base, the business either should really pay attention to updating their online banking features to better cater to the goals of this group.
      • While having the second largest number of credit cards and credit limit, they make up +58% of customers meaning that they are the largest source of revenue
      • By making online banking more accessible to this group, the business would facilitate accessing their client base through promotions. As of now, their biggest group would mainly hear about new offers through physical visits to the bank.
      • Another way of going about this, is making the personal touch much more accessible (would likely be more expensive than updating online features)
